document_data.Inception:
The term came from the belief it was granted by the gods of [[Toril]].{{Cite web/theedverse/2024-02-06 - Divine Gifts}} While most priests preached the Gift came from the gods, divine action seldom bestowed the Gift permanently.{{Cite web/theedverse/2021-02-13 - The Art Means Arcane Magic}}

It was possible to breed a population for higher likelihood of the Gift, and people with mages in their ascendance were more likely to display it, but even Mystra and [[Azuth]] working in concert did not have the power to make it a sure thing.{{Cite archive/Greenwood's Grotto/2023-07-02/Wizard breeding programs}} [[Sorcerer]]s, in particular, were often considered to have draconic ancestors. Other processes were considered liable to add to the possibilities of an individual being born Gifted; those included inserting dweomer-bearing objects into the mother's body beforehand, or the parents wearing [[enchanted]] underwear prior to conception, or having [[spell]]s cast on the gestating mother frequently. None of them was assured of working.{{cite web/theedverse/2019/03-05 - Spellscar inheritability}}

Notably, the Gift wasn't equal for everyone, and some magicians bore greater innate power and affinity than others.{{Cite web/theedverse/2021-05-19 - On Arcane Healing}}

document_data.Awakening:
Of those who had the Gift, only around a third displayed it from birth, while the majority would see it awaken at some point in their lives.{{Cite web/theedverse/2024-02-06 - The Gift Across Life}} Those who were affected by spells, or handled [[magical item]]s, were more likely to awaken their Gift.{{Cite web/theedverse/2024-03-28 - Methods of granting the Gift}} Practicing magic constantly also made that one more likely,{{Cite web/theedverse/2024-09-18 - Practice awakening the Gift}} though it had only been the path for a rare few.{{cite web/theedverse/2024-09-18 - Rare study Gift awakeninga}}

It was believed the Gift could not be stolen; however, magical ability was in fact known to have been gained only at another's expense on a number of occasions.{{cite book/Castle Spulzeer}} On the occasions when people realized powers they did not have before, such events were widely understood as an awakening of a latent Gift rather than a newly created Gift.{{Cite web/theedverse/2021-10-22 - Stealing and Awakening the Gift}} Only more extreme methods, such as replacing much of one's blood with that of a creature to which the Gift was inherent, such as a [[dragon]], were regarded as instilling a Gift where one wasn't present.{{Cite web/theedverse/2024-02-07 - Awakening the Gift}}

A latent gift sometimes manifested, for those sufficiently studied and practiced in the Weave, in a dim ability to feel the ebb and flow of magic when in dreams. The Gift was also necessary for attuning to certain spell-unleashing devices, or perhaps to all enchanted miscellanea.{{cite web/theedverse/2024-08-18 - Giftless and Magic Items}}

document_data.Frequency:
[[File:Netherese baking.png|thumb|right|300px|''In ancient Netheril, basic magical aptitude was standard.'']]
The amount of people who had the Gift varied, but they were rare; in the Sword Coast during the late 15{{th}} century [[DR]], the reported ratio of people with the Gift was about 1 in 9,000, and not even half of them would ever develop it.{{cite web/theedverse/2020/12-30 - Arcane Demographics}} In contrasting, in some extensively magical races, such as [[elves]], [[triton]]s, or [[tiefling]]s, the Gift was held by a majority of their members.{{Cite web/theedverse/2021-01-23 - Rarity of demihuman wizards}} Later numbers, taking into account numerous magical catastrophes, put the numbers of the Gifted somewhere under six percent of the populace.{{cite archive/Greenwood's Grotto/2024-08-09/The Gift Population Ratio}}

In ancient [[Netheril]], almost every member of [[human]] society was able and expected to wield at least a few basic [[cantra]]s. This carried through to the descendants of Netheril; the [[Shadovar]] of [[Thultanthar]] also had a widespread basic affinity with arcane magic, with even common soldiers having at least some ability. [[Halruaa]], too, showed an extremely high frequency of arcanists; about one-third of them were said to cast at least one spell as of {{yearlink|1367}}, a number that held in {{yearlink|1372}}.{{cite book/Shining South|129}}

document_data.In Society:
Some societies actively tested children for the Gift, including [[Thay]]. Every citizen of Thay was tested in their infancy.{{Cite web/theedverse/2022-07-04 - Non-human Red Wizards}}{{Cite archive/Greenwood's Grotto/2023-10-06/Non-humans in Thay}}

The [[Harpers]] sought out those with the Gift, especially those who might be interested in joining.{{Cite web/theedverse/2022-11-02 - Harpers seeking Wizards}}

Amongst [[ixzan]]s, the demonrays of the Underdark, wizard ixzans had an intuitive sense for magical ability in young ixzan. On identifying one, they would defend the nascent spellcaster ferociously against others in their cruel society.<ref>

document_data.Notable or Assumed Giftless:
* [[Archlis]], a [[magelord]], was accused of having no magic of his own by the [[genasi]] [[wizard]] [[Gunderal]], claiming all he had were "stolen charms and looted trinkets." Whether it was true or not, the insult appeared to hit home for him.
* The [[Yhaunn]]ian scion [[Keph Thingoleir]] was not able to learn or cast any arcane magic, despite all his siblings and his parents being capable of wizardry.{{Cite web/Character Profile: At Home in Fourstaves House}} Instead, he had a powerful affinity for [[the Power]].
* The [[Cormyte]] nobleman [[Sardasper Halaunt]], despite all his ambitions, was never able to master any magic to the day he died.{{cite book/Spellstorm||13}}
